  "prompt": "What are the books that should be read by everyone?",
  "response": "There are numerous books that are often recommended as must-reads due to their cultural, philosophical, and educational value. Here are some that are frequently suggested:\n\n1. **\"To Kill a Mockingbird\" by Harper Lee** - A profound novel that deals with serious issues such as racial inequality and moral growth.\n   \n2. **\"1984\" by George Orwell** - A dystopian novel that explores themes of totalitarianism, surveillance, and individuality.\n   \n3. **\"Pride and Prejudice\" by Jane Austen** - A classic novel that offers insights into romantic entanglements and societal expectations in the 19th century.\n   \n4. **\"The Great Gatsby\" by F. Scott Fitzgerald** - This novel captures the Jazz Age and offers a critique of the American Dream.\n   \n5. **\"One Hundred Years of Solitude\" by Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez** - A landmark in magical realism that traces the Buend\u00eda family through several generations.\n   \n6. **\"Moby-Dick\" by Herman Melville** - A complex, symbolic narrative of one man's obsession with defeating a massive whale.\n   \n7. **\"War and Peace\" by Leo Tolstoy** - An epic novel that covers a broad swath of Russian society during the Napoleonic Era.\n   \n8. **\"The Catcher in the Rye\" by J.D. Salinger** - A novel exploring themes of teenage angst and alienation in the post-war period.\n   \n9. **\"The Lord of the Rings\" by J.R.R. Tolkien** - A monumental work of fantasy literature that has influenced the genre profoundly.\n   \n10. **\"Beloved\" by Toni Morrison** - A powerful narrative about the legacy of slavery and the quest for identity and self-understanding.\n   \n11. **\"Brave New World\" by Aldous Huxley** - A dystopian vision of a future shaped by technological and genetic control.\n   \n12. **\"Jane Eyre\" by Charlotte Bront\u00eb** - A novel that combines romance with a critique of Victorian social norms.\n\n13. **\"Catch-22\" by Joseph Heller** - A satirical novel set during World War II, it provides a powerful commentary on the absurdity of war.\n\n14. **\"Crime and Punishment\" by Fyodor Dostoevsky** - A deep dive into guilt, morality, and redemption.\n\n15. **\"The Alchemist\" by Paulo Coelho** - A philosophical book about following one's dreams and fulfilling one's destiny.\n\nThese books span various genres and time periods, offering diverse insights into human nature, societal issues, and the world around us.",
